{"title_page": "Oberheim OB-Xa", "text_new": "{{Infobox synthesizer\n|image = \n|image_caption = \n|synth_name =  OB-Xa\n|synth_manufacturer = [[Oberheim]]\n|synthesis_type = [[Analog synthesizer|Analog]] [[Subtractive synthesis|Subtractive]]\n|polyphony = 4, 6 or 8 voices\n|timbrality = Bitimbral\n|oscillator = 2 VCOs per voice\n|filter = Switchable 12dB/oct and 24dB/oct resonant low-pass\n|attenuator = 2 x ADSR; one for VCF, one for VCA\n|left_control = Pitch<br>Modulation\n|lfo = 2\n|keyboard = 61-key\n|velocity\t= No\n|aftertouch = No\n|memory = 32 - 120 patches\n|ext_control = Oberheim system\n|fx = None\n|dates = 1980 - 1982\n|price = [[US$]]4595 - [[US$]]5595\n}}\n\nThe '''Oberheim OB-Xa''' was a [[synthesizer]] created by the [[Oberheim]] company as an overhaul of their first compact synthesizer, the [[Oberheim OB-X|OB-X]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/us/news/tech/blast-from-the-past-oberheim-ob-xa-601472|title=Blast from the past: Oberheim OB-Xa - MusicRadar|website=Musicradar.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/us/news/tech/obxd-free-vst-plugin-synth-inspired-by-oberheim-ob-x-594880|title=Obxd: free VST plugin synth inspired by Oberheim OB-X - MusicRadar|website=Musicradar.com}}</ref>\n\nThe OB-Xa was released in December 1980, a year after the OB-X was released. Instead of discrete circuits for oscillators and filters, the OB-Xa (and the Oberheim synths to follow) switched to [[Curtis CEM|Curtis]] [[integrated circuit]]s. This made the inside of the synth less cluttered, facilitating troubleshooting, and reducing the cost of manufacture. It was getting more difficult to service the OB-Xa due to the scarcity of Curtis chips; however, Curtis  in June 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.curtiselectromusic.com/|title=Home|website=Curtis Electromusic Specialties|accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>, Coolaudio<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coolaudio.com/features-page.php?product=V3340D|title=V3340D Voltage Controlled Oscillator|accessdate=27th April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coolaudio.com/features-page.php?product=V3320|title=V3320 Voltage Controlled Filter|accessdate=27th April 2020}}</ref> and Alfa<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alfarzpp.lv/eng/sc/semiconductor.php|title=Semiconductor production|accessdate=27th April 2020}}</ref> all started re-manufacturing some of these chips which has breathed new life into the longevity of the OB-Xa and many other synthesizers that use these chips.\n\nAside from hardware changes, the OB-Xa had better interface features than the OB-X. These included being able to split the keyboard into two halves with different voices and the ability to layer voices to create thicker sound (essentially making two notes sound for every key pressed). Polyphony stayed the same - again 4, 6 and 8-voice models were offered.\n\nOne function that did disappear from the OB-X voice architecture was cross modulation, or frequency modulation of the first VCO with the second VCO. When done with analogue circuits, it's a unique sound made famous by the [[Sequential Circuits]] [[Prophet 5]] and its poly-mod section which is considerably more flexible and dynamic than the basic implementation offered in the OBX. In place of this feature on the OB-Xa front panel is Filter Envelope modulation for oscillator 2, which allows the pitch to be modulated by the envelope. Another new feature to the OB-Xa is a second filter mode labeled \"4 Pole\".\n\nIn May 2019, [[Behringer]] announced their wish to release a [[synthesizer clone]] of the OB-Xa called the UB-XA.<ref name=UBXA>{{cite magazine|ref={{sfnref|Gear News|2018}}|title=Behringer UB-Xa \u2013 first photos of their completed Oberheim clone|url=https://www.gearnews.com/behringer-ub-xa-first-photos-of-their-completed-oberheim-clone/}}</ref>\nPhotos of a tooling-complete unit were shown on 27th April 2020.<ref name=UBXA2>{{cite web|title=UB-Xa Update.|url=https://www.facebook.com/behringer/posts/10158372766108914}}</ref>\n\n==Albums that feature the OB-Xa==\n{{colbegin|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Laurie Anderson]] - ''[[Big Science (Laurie Anderson album)|Big Science]]'' (1982)\n*[[Bon Jovi]] - ''[[Bon Jovi (album)|Bon Jovi]]'' (1984)\n*[[David Bowie]] - ''[[Tonight (David Bowie album)|Tonight]] (1984)\n*[[Joe Cocker]] - ''[[Civilized Man]]'' (1984)\n*[[Miles Davis]] - ''[[Star People]]'' (1983)\n*[[Miles Davis]] - ''[[Decoy (album)|Decoy]]'' (1984)\n*[[Miles Davis]] - ''[[You're Under Arrest (Miles Davis album)|You're Under Arrest]]'' (1985)\n*[[Paul Davis (singer)|Paul Davis]] - ''[[Cool Night]]'' (1981)\n*[[Electric Light Orchestra]] - ''[[Time (Electric Light Orchestra album)|Time]]'' (1981)\n*[[Electric Light Orchestra]] - ''[[Secret Messages]]'' (1983)\n*[[Endgames (band)|Endgames]] - ''Building Beauty'' (1983)\n*[[Brad Fiedel]] - ''[[The Terminator#Soundtrack|The Terminator]]'' - Soundtrack (1984)\n*[[F. R. David]] - ''[[Words (F. R. David album)|Words]]'' (1982)\n*[[Bruce Hornsby#The Range|Bruce Hornsby & the Range]] - ''[[The Way It Is (Bruce Hornsby album)|The Way It Is]]'' (1986)\n*[[Billy Idol]] - ''[[Rebel Yell (album)|Rebel Yell]]'' (1983)\n*[[Mick Jagger]] - ''[[She's the Boss]]'' (1985)\n*[[Jean Michel Jarre]] - ''[[The Concerts in China]]'' (1982)\n*[[Jean Michel Jarre]] - ''[[Zoolook]]'' (1984)\n*[[Nik Kershaw]] - ''[[Human Racing]]'' (1984)\n*[[Chaka Khan]] - ''[[I Feel for You (album)|I Feel for You]]'' (1984)\n*[[Evelyn \"Champagne\" King|Evelyn King]] - ''[[Get Loose (album)|Get Loose]]'' (1982)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Evelyn-King-Get-Loose/release/295234|title=Evelyn King - Get Loose|website=Discogs.com}}</ref>\n*[[Material (band)|Material]] - ''[[One Down]]'' (1982)\n*[[Mezzoforte (band)|Mezzoforte]] - ''[[Surprise Surprise (album)|Surprise Surprise]]'' (1982)\n*[[Naked Eyes]] - ''[[Burning Bridges (Naked Eyes album)|Burning Bridges]]'' (1983)\n*[[New Musik]] - ''[[Warp (album)|Warp]]'' (1982)\n*[[Stevie Nicks]] - ''[[The Wild Heart (album)|The Wild Heart]]'' (1983)\n*[[Gary Numan]] - ''[[I, Assassin]]'' (1982)\n*[[Gary Numan]] - ''[[Warriors (Gary Numan album)|Warriors]]'' (1983)\n*[[Mike Oldfield]] - ''[[Crises (Mike Oldfield album)|Crises]]'' (1983)\n*[[Mike Oldfield]] - ''[[Discovery (Mike Oldfield album)|Discovery]]'' (1984)\n*[[Mike Oldfield]] - ''[[The Killing Fields (album)|The Killing Fields]]'' - Soundtrack (1984)\n*[[Prince (musician)|Prince]] - ''[[1999 (Prince album)|1999]]'' (1982)\n*[[Prince (musician)|Prince]] - ''[[Purple Rain (album)|Purple Rain]]'' (1984)\n*[[Queen (band)|Queen]] - ''[[Hot Space]]'' (1982)\n*[[Queen (band)|Queen]] - ''[[The Works (Queen album)|The Works]]'' (1984)\n*[[Rush (band)|Rush]] - ''[[Grace Under Pressure (Rush album)|Grace Under Pressure]]'' (1984)\n*[[Rush (band)|Rush]] - ''[[Signals (Rush album)|Signals]]'' (1982)\n*[[Scandal (American band)|Scandal]] - \"[[Goodbye to You (Scandal song)|Goodbye to You]]\" (1982)\n*[[Ser\u00fa Gir\u00e1n]] - ''[[Peperina]]'' (1981)\n*[[Silent Running (band)|Silent Running]] - ''[[Shades of Liberty]]'' (1984)\n*[[Simple Minds]] - ''[[New Gold Dream (81\u201382\u201383\u201384)|New Gold Dream (81/82/83/84)]]'' (1982)\n*Simple Minds - ''[[Sparkle in the Rain]]'' (1984)\n*Simple Minds - ''[[Once Upon a Time (Simple Minds album)|Once Upon a Time]]'' (1985)\n*[[Rod Stewart]] - ''[[Tonight I'm Yours]]'' (1981)\n*[[Styx (band)|Styx]] - ''[[Kilroy Was Here (album)|Kilroy Was Here]]'' (1983)\n*[[Talk Talk (band)|Talk Talk]] - ''[[The Party's Over (Talk Talk album)|The Party's Over]]'' (1982)\n*[[The Police (band)|The Police]] - ''[[Ghost in the Machine (The Police album)|Ghost in the Machine]]'' (1981)\n*[[The Police (band)|The Police]] - ''[[Synchronicity (The Police album)|Synchronicity]]'' (1983)\n*[[The System (band)|The System]] - ''[[Sweat (The System album)|Sweat]]'' (1983)\n*[[The Stranglers]] - ''[[Feline (The Stranglers album)|Feline]]'' (1983)\n*[[The Stranglers]] - ''[[Aural Sculpture]]'' (1984)\n*[[The Time (band)|The Time]] - '